research/history_archive/rollback_to_pre_round38_20260321_124110/memory.json:737:    "round 32: Severe stagnation and two non-competitive K=128 architecture probes suggest the current global-ranking support mechanisms are locally exhausted. A new `group_topk` prototype that enforces one local winner per small latent group before the global top-k may reduce redundant feature selection and improve reconstruction quality or cost under the same validated training regime. -> crash (fvu=None, observed_fvu=None, k=None, health=crash, termination=invalid_env_overrides)",
research/history_archive/rollback_to_pre_round38_20260321_124110/memory.json:741:    "round 33: After nine non-improving rounds and non-competitive K=128 results from topk and routed, the current global support-ranking direction looks structurally weak. The newly added `group_topk` family is the next fundamentally different architecture probe because it imposes local winner-take-all competition before global selection, which may improve feature diversity and reduce redundant support allocation under the same validated training regime. -> crash (fvu=None, observed_fvu=None, k=None, health=crash, termination=invalid_env_overrides)",
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0010.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"hybrid_topk may now be limited by using the nonlinear branch only as an additive correction; letting it multiplicatively modulate the linear logits should improve support shaping while preserving the strong baseline path. Re-test hybrid_topk at the best-known K=128, expansion_factor=8, optimizer=adam setting after this targeted hybrid-family stabilization edit.","summary":"The expansion_factor=16 follow-up did not improve full FVU and cost substantial throughput, so the next move should be a targeted architecture refinement rather than more brute-force scaling. This round keeps the winning hybrid_topk Adam ef=8 setup and upgrades the nonlinear branch to modulate linear logits as well as add residual logits.","change_type":"edit_architecture","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is a narrow, defensible follow-up on the current best family and it directly addresses the likely limit of the present hybrid design without reopening the broader search space. It still adds encoder complexity, so any quality gain will need later cost scrutiny against the ef=8 Adam mainline.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/hybrid_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["hybrid_topk with Adam and expansion_factor=16 achieved better proxy FVU but slightly worse full FVU (0.1623645443469286 vs 0.16189537942409515) and a clear throughput regression, so brute-force scaling is not the next priority.","Round 10 stabilizes hybrid_topk by adding a zero-initialized multiplicative modulation path on top of the existing additive nonlinear residual, keeping the model anchored to the proven linear encoder at initialization."],"next_hypotheses":["If the modulated hybrid_topk improves proxy FVU, promote it to full as the next mainline quality candidate.","If the modulated hybrid_topk is flat or worse, keep the current hybrid_topk Adam ef=8 checkpoint as mainline and revisit training dynamics or a genuinely new family instead of more local hybrid edits."]}
research/history_archive/14_20260326_184609/logs/agent_action_0002.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A modest LR reduction from 8e-4 to 6e-4 may improve the topk K=128 EF=12 signum training trajectory by reducing late-stage noise or overshoot while preserving the current architecture and optimizer.","summary":"Keep the topk mainline recipe fixed and run a single-variable learning-rate probe at LR=6e-4 against the K=128 EF=12 signum baseline.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the prescribed mainline order after the clean baseline and changes only LR. The prompt does not expose detailed curve-shape metrics, so this is the more conservative LR probe before considering optimizer changes.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"6e-4"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 2 asks one question only: whether a modest LR reduction improves the topk K=128 EF=12 signum curve relative to the clean baseline."],"next_hypotheses":["If LR=6e-4 improves stability but converges too slowly, test LR=1e-3 as the opposite single-axis LR probe before changing optimizer.","If the LR sweep does not improve the topk mainline, keep LR anchored and test OPTIMIZER=adam as the next single-variable change."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0019.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The round-18 refined_topk crash was caused by a mixed-precision implementation bug in the ridge solve, not by evidence against the architecture. Running the small support-wise solve in float32 and casting the refined coefficients back to the model dtype should make the family trainable under bf16 autocast, allowing a valid proxy read on whether coefficient refitting can lower FVU at K=128.","summary":"Keep refined_topk alive for one crash-recovery follow-up. The architecture stays the same, but its coefficient-refinement solve is now executed in a stable float32 path so the proxy run can test the actual quality hypothesis instead of failing on dtype mismatch.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"refined_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is a narrow implementation-fix round on the most recent crashing family, which is the right move after a first-run failure with a clear stack trace. The main risk is that the architecture may still be weak even after the fix, but a clean rerun is more informative than abandoning the family based on a bf16/autocast bug.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"refined_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/refined_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 19 fixes a refined_topk mixed-precision bug: the support-wise ridge solve now runs in float32 and casts refined coefficients back to the model dtype.","The refined_topk crash in round 18 came from a bf16/float32 mismatch inside torch.linalg.solve under autocast, so that round should not be treated as architecture evidence.","A local bf16 import/forward/backward sanity check passed for the fixed refined_topk implementation before handing control back to the runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If the fixed refined_topk yields a meaningful proxy FVU gain, follow with a family-specific stabilization pass on regularization strength or support source before considering promotion.","If refined_topk now runs normally but lands near the recent 0.275 proxy plateau, conclude that coefficient refitting alone is insufficient and pivot to a genuinely different encoder family next round."]}
