research/history_archive/14_20260326_184609/logs/agent_action_0003.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The baseline topk K=128 EF=12 signum recipe may be slightly underpowered at LR=8e-4; increasing LR to 1e-3 can test whether the worse 6e-4 result came from under-training rather than instability.","summary":"Keep the topk mainline recipe fixed and run the opposite single-variable learning-rate probe at LR=1e-3 for K=128 EF=12 with signum.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the prescribed mainline path: same family, same K, same optimizer, one LR-only question. Since 6e-4 regressed, the most informative next move is to bracket the baseline from the other side before switching optimizers.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1e-3"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 3 isolates the opposite LR direction to determine whether the topk mainline is limited by under-training at 8e-4 or already near its best signum LR."],"next_hypotheses":["If LR=1e-3 also fails to beat the baseline, keep LR at 8e-4 and test OPTIMIZER=adam as the next single-variable change.","If LR=1e-3 improves early progress but degrades late stability, try a milder LR increase such as 9e-4 only if another LR round is still justified before optimizer swap."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/14_20260326_184609/logs/agent_action_0001.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The reference topk recipe at K=128, EF=12, signum, LR=8e-4 should provide a clean first quality-anchor curve and runtime baseline; that anchor is needed before any LR or optimizer retuning can be interpreted.","summary":"Run a clean mainline topk baseline at K=128 / EF=12 with signum and LR=8e-4 to establish the first curve-shape and runtime anchor for this session.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This round is calibration-first rather than improvement-first. It intentionally avoids introducing a confounded recipe change so the next LR move can be chosen from actual curve shape instead of guesswork.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"8e-4"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Use this run as the clean topk curve and runtime anchor before any LR or optimizer comparison."],"next_hypotheses":["If the curve is stable but plateaus early, keep topk fixed and test a single-axis LR reduction to 6e-4.","If the curve is still improving late and remains smooth, keep topk fixed and test a single-axis LR increase to 1e-3 before changing optimizer."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0009.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"hybrid_topk with Adam is now the strongest K=128 configuration, so the next quality-first move is to increase representational capacity rather than shrink K or chase cost. Test hybrid_topk at K=128 with Adam and expansion_factor=16 to see whether extra latent capacity can materially reduce FVU again.","summary":"The hybrid_topk Adam stabilization produced a meaningful full improvement to 0.1619 FVU, but that is still far from the aggressive target. This round keeps the best family and optimizer fixed and spends one proxy run on a larger expansion factor as the cleanest quality-first scaling test.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is the right next bet because the current mainline finally has momentum and deserves capacity scaling before any lower-K or cost tradeoffs. The main risk is that extra capacity may give only marginal quality gains relative to added memory and compute.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["hybrid_topk plus Adam improved the full K=128 frontier to FVU 0.16189537942409515 with no runtime regression relative to the prior hybrid run.","Round 9 escalates capacity within the leading family by testing expansion_factor=16 at fixed K=128 and Adam before considering any lower-K or cost-driven moves."],"next_hypotheses":["If hybrid_topk with Adam and expansion_factor=16 improves proxy FVU, promote it to full as the new mainline quality candidate.","If the larger expansion factor is flat or only marginally better, keep hybrid_topk as mainline and look for a more targeted architectural improvement rather than scaling capacity further."]}
research/history_archive/14_20260326_184609/logs/agent_action_0006.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Adam appears to be the better optimizer for topk at K=128 EF=12, and the 8e-4 callback landed very close to the 1e-3 anchor. A smaller follow-up LR reduction to 9e-4 can answer whether the adam optimum lies between those two settings rather than at either endpoint.","summary":"Keep the topk mainline fixed at K=128 EF=12 with adam and run one more narrow LR refinement at 9e-4 to bracket the best adam operating point.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This keeps the family, K, EF, and optimizer fixed and asks one remaining LR question before moving on to other axes. The 8e-4 result was close enough to the 1e-3 anchor that an in-between LR is the most interpretable next probe.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"9e-4"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 6 narrows the adam LR search between 8e-4 and 1e-3 for the current topk K=128 EF=12 mainline."],"next_hypotheses":["If 9e-4 does not clearly beat the existing adam anchor, stop LR tuning and move to a single loss/preprocess-related parameter next.","If 9e-4 improves again, keep adam as mainline and only then consider whether another very small LR refinement is still justified."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0018.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Recent architecture edits have mostly tried to improve support selection, yet multiple distinct families have converged to the same proxy FVU plateau under normal runtime. A stronger next bet is that support is not the main bottleneck at K=128; instead, the selected coefficients are too crude. A refined_topk family that keeps the proven linear top-k support but recomputes the chosen coefficients with a small per-example ridge solve against the decoder atoms could materially lower FVU by directly reducing reconstruction error on the selected support.","summary":"Pivot away from branch-union follow-ups and add a new refined_topk family. It preserves the baseline linear top-k proposal, but replaces the final coefficients with a ridge-refined fit on the chosen decoder features, targeting reconstruction quality directly rather than adding more routing machinery. This is a single proxy prototype for a more radical quality-first hypothesis at the K=128 anchor.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"refined_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a coherent architecture pivot after two flat union_topk rounds under normal runtime. The main risk is that the per-example solve may add overhead or overfit weak supports, but it tests a meaningfully different failure hypothesis than the recent support-selection families and keeps the launcher interface unchanged.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"refined_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/refined_topk_sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/config.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/__init__.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 18 adds a new refined_topk family that keeps the baseline linear top-k support but refits the selected coefficients with a small ridge solve against the decoder atoms.","The refined_topk implementation uses a straight-through blend so the forward path uses refined coefficients while preserving gradient flow through the baseline top-k activations.","A local import/forward/backward sanity check passed for refined_topk before handing control back to the runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If refined_topk materially improves proxy FVU, follow with a family-specific stabilization pass on the coefficient refinement strength or support source before considering promotion.","If refined_topk is flat or regresses under normal runtime, that is evidence that coefficient refitting alone is not enough and the next round should pivot to a genuinely different encoder family rather than more top-k refinements."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0004.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A factorized nonlinear encoder may lower FVU at K=128 by adding a hidden mixing stage before latent scoring, giving the encoder more expressive feature composition while keeping the fixed-K decode path unchanged. Test factorized_topk at the same K=128 anchor point as the next quality-first family.","summary":"Both mixture_topk and residual_topk archived under normal runtime with proxy FVU near the topk proxy anchor, so the next move is another architecture family rather than smaller-K search. factorized_topk is the clearest remaining low-friction expressivity upgrade in the current codebase.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is still exploratory, but it continues the right search pattern: hold K fixed, change one architectural idea, and see whether encoder expressivity can move proxy FVU. If this also comes back flat, the current built-in families are not yet showing a path to the target.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["residual_topk at K=128/ef8/signum archived under normal runtime with proxy FVU 0.3055884689092636, so the residual two-branch prototype did not improve on the anchor.","Round 4 opens factorized_topk as the next expressive family to test at fixed K=128 before considering lower-K or cost-driven moves."],"next_hypotheses":["If factorized_topk improves proxy FVU, follow with a stabilization pass on optimizer or expansion factor before promotion.","If factorized_topk is also flat or worse, shift from parameter-only family swapping to a code edit that introduces a genuinely new encoder family or materially changes one incubating family."]}
research/history_archive/14_20260326_184609/logs/agent_action_0005.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Now that adam at K=128 EF=12 outperforms signum at LR=1e-3, a modest LR reduction to 8e-4 may improve late-stage convergence and test whether the current adam result is slightly overshooting its best operating point.","summary":"Keep the topk mainline fixed at K=128 EF=12 with adam and run a single-variable LR callback from 1e-3 to 8e-4.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the prescribed order after an optimizer win: keep the new optimizer and perform one LR callback before touching other axes. The round isolates LR only, with family, K, EF, and optimizer held constant.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"8e-4"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 5 tests whether adam's improved topk result at K=128 EF=12 benefits from a slightly lower LR than 1e-3."],"next_hypotheses":["If adam at 8e-4 improves further, keep adam as mainline and consider one more narrow LR refinement only if the curve still suggests room.","If adam at 8e-4 regresses, retain adam LR=1e-3 as the mainline anchor and defer further LR tuning until after loss or preprocess questions become justified."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0013.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A gated SAE may materially lower proxy FVU at K=128 by decoupling support selection from coefficient magnitude, letting one branch learn which features should fire while another learns how strongly they should reconstruct. After two flat jumprelu stabilization rounds and stalled hybrid local search, this is the cleanest untried quality-first family already supported by the execution layer.","summary":"JumpReLU did not produce a meaningful stabilization gain, and recent local tuning around the current hybrid mainline has not closed the quality gap. This round shifts to a new existing architecture family with a distinct encoder bias: independent gating and magnitude branches at the same K=128/ef=8/Adam anchor, evaluated first as a proxy quality probe.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a single coherent family exploration, not another weak local sweep. The main risk is that sigmoid-gated selection could saturate and undertrain, but the architectural change is clean, already implemented, and directly targets support quality rather than cost.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 13 opens the previously untested gated family as a quality-first K=128 proxy probe after jumprelu threshold tuning remained flat around 0.275 proxy FVU.","The gated architecture decouples latent support selection from activation magnitude, which is a substantively different encoder bias from hybrid additive correction and jumprelu thresholding."],"next_hypotheses":["If gated shows a strong proxy signal, promote it to full before returning to smaller-K or cost work.","If gated is also weak, bias the next round toward another genuinely different encoder family or a code edit for a new architecture rather than more parameter-only tuning on recent families."]}
research/history_archive/14_20260326_184609/logs/agent_action_0004.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"With topk K=128 EF=12 now showing a better anchor at signum LR=1e-3, switching only the optimizer to adam can test whether the remaining gap is optimization-limited rather than learning-rate-limited.","summary":"Keep the topk mainline recipe fixed at K=128 EF=12 LR=1e-3 and run a single-variable optimizer swap from signum to adam.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the prescribed mainline order: after establishing the better LR anchor, the next clean question is optimizer choice. LR, K, and family stay fixed so any curve or FVU change can be attributed to the optimizer.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"1e-3"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 4 isolates optimizer choice at the current best topk anchor: K=128, EF=12, LR=1e-3."],"next_hypotheses":["If adam improves the curve or final FVU, keep adam fixed and do one LR callback for adam next.","If adam underperforms signum at the same LR, retain signum as mainline and only revisit optimizer later if curve shape suggests a specific failure mode."],"primary_variable":"optimizer"}
