research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0058.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`residual_topk` did not fail on quality or runtime grounds; it failed because the execution layer still does not recognize the architecture name. The smallest informative next move is a narrow code-fix round that registers and wires `residual_topk` into the existing config/class dispatch and forward path so the prototype can finally receive one real K=128 proxy measurement under the current strongest regime.","summary":"Register and implement the `residual_topk` architecture in `sparsify/`, then rerun the same K=128 proxy prototype under the current best signum settings.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"residual_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is the minimal blocker-removal step after a concrete architecture-registration crash, and it keeps the round focused on making the intended new family runnable rather than changing the experimental target. The main risk is that a second incompatibility appears after registration, but that is still better handled as a code-fix path than by abandoning the family without a valid signal.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"residual_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 57 produced a concrete execution-layer blocker for `residual_topk`: the architecture name is still missing from `SparseCoderConfig` validation and/or SAE class dispatch, so the family has no usable quality signal yet.","This is stronger evidence of incomplete code integration than of a bad architecture, so `residual_topk` should not be judged on quality yet.","The next round keeps the original `residual_topk` K=128 proxy target fixed and changes only the code needed to make the family selectable and runnable by the existing launcher."],"next_hypotheses":["If `residual_topk` runs and shows promising proxy FVU, keep the family alive and stabilize its internal K split next.","If it runs cleanly but is clearly worse than gated and not better than factorized-topk, archive it quickly and move to another architecture family.","If `residual_topk` still fails after registration is fixed, treat the remaining issue as a deeper implementation incompatibility and shift effort elsewhere."],"primary_variable":"code_fix"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0030.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A clean rerun of the matched `gated` baseline at `K=128, EF=12, optimizer=signum, lr=1.6e-3` will tell us whether Round 29 was a stable result with a healthy curve shape or a one-off; if it reproduces near 0.1499 with smooth descent, we should keep `gated` on the mainline and start the LR sweep next.","summary":"Round 29 already established the first matched `gated` control and it slightly leads the current frontier at `K=128`, so the highest-value next step is not to branch or change K, but to pay the clean-baseline tax the strategy asks for. This answers one question only: whether `gated` is genuinely competitive under the reference recipe, judged by both final FVU and the training-curve shape.","change_type":"no_change","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the required family, keeps EF fixed at 12, does not touch K, and follows the requested sequencing by filling the clean baseline before LR or optimizer changes. I am intentionally not proposing a new LR yet because reproducibility and curve shape are the blocking question after a first promising gated run.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 30 should be a clean control rerun for gated at the matched reference recipe: K=128, EF=12, signum, LR=1.6e-3.","Use the rerun to inspect trajectory shape, not just terminal FVU; only start the LR sweep if the baseline reproduces cleanly."],"next_hypotheses":["If the clean rerun reproduces with a smooth curve, try a conservative LR callback within gated, starting with 1.2e-3.","If the clean rerun is clearly worse or unstable versus Round 29, archive gated quickly and return to the topk mainline."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history_archive/10_20260321_011318/logs/agent_action_0004.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At the restored K=128 TopK anchor, switching from signum to Adam may improve optimization quality enough to lower FVU relative to the new 0.1955 full baseline before exploring smaller K or cost reductions.","summary":"Run a proxy optimizer comparison at the stable K=128 TopK anchor by changing only the optimizer from signum to Adam.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline_comparison","self_review":"This is still a local optimization move, so the upside may be limited relative to a strong architecture change. It is justified now because the baseline is stable again and optimizer is the cleanest single-variable test.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"6e-4"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["TopK with signum at LR=6e-4 established the current full K=128 anchor at FVU 0.19545910321176052.","With stability restored, the next clean comparison is optimizer-only at the same K=128 anchor rather than rewarding smaller K.","Judge this round strictly on FVU improvement versus the restored TopK baseline, not on cost or sparsity changes."],"next_hypotheses":["If Adam improves proxy FVU, promote to full and then consider a small LR sweep within Adam.","If Adam is neutral or worse, pivot back to architecture exploration rather than spending many more rounds on TopK optimizer tuning.","If Adam is unstable, retain signum as the mainline optimizer anchor and explore a different architecture family next."],"primary_variable":"optimizer"}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0063.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Crash recovery mode requires returning to the strongest working gated path and making only a minor parameter adjustment. The least-risk informative move is to keep the K=128 gated signum anchor fixed and restore a small auxiliary loss with `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` to check whether the canonical regularized regime improves training stability or quality without reopening architecture risk.","summary":"Run a gated proxy recovery pass at `K=128` with the current best signum setup and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` to recheck stability on the strongest working family.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This follows crash recovery constraints by avoiding code edits and staying on the best validated family with one small parameter change. The main risk is low novelty, but restoring clean signal on a stable configuration is more important than broader exploration after consecutive crashes.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Crash recovery mode overrides architecture exploration for this round and requires a param-only run on the strongest known working configuration.","The best validated anchor remains gated EF=16, K=128, signum, LR=1.6e-3; this round changes only AUXK_ALPHA to probe a conservative recovery variant.","Recent residual-topk crashes should continue to be treated as unresolved implementation-path failures rather than evidence against the stable gated baseline."],"next_hypotheses":["If the gated recovery run is healthy and competitive, resume frontier work from the stable gated family before attempting new architecture exploration again.","If `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` regresses versus the aux-free anchor, keep `AUXK_ALPHA=0` as the main K=128 recovery baseline.","If stability is restored cleanly, the next move can revisit adjacent low-risk gated comparisons before reopening blocked architecture paths."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0022.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 21 showed that `topk/signum/LR=1.6e-3/EF=12` at `K=96` is a promising high-quality reduced-cost point: its curve kept descending smoothly through the late phase, and both `dead_pct` and `auxk` stayed very low. This round changes only the loss-shaping axis, lowering `AUXK_ALPHA` from `0.03125` to `0.015625` while keeping the `K=96` recipe fixed, to answer whether the new near-anchor deployment point is slightly over-regularized and can recover a bit more reconstruction quality without destabilizing training.","summary":"Run a single loss-axis test on the newly validated `K=96` topk point: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `K=96`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and reduce `AUXK_ALPHA` to `0.015625` to see whether weaker auxiliary pressure improves the high-quality reduced-cost recipe.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the active `topk` family, changes exactly one primary variable (`other_param` via `AUXK_ALPHA`), respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and follows directly from the observed `K=96` curve shape. The main risk is that the gain may be small, but `K=96` is now the most promising reduced-cost point and its very low dead-feature pressure makes a clean over-regularization check more justified than continuing to remap K.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"K","value":"96"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.015625"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 21 established `K=96` as a strong high-quality reduced-cost point: late-phase FVU kept descending smoothly and both `dead_pct` and `auxk` remained near zero.","Because `K=96` is not capacity-stressed like the low-K regime, it is a better place than `K=8` or `K=16` to test whether the current auxiliary dead-feature pressure is slightly too strong.","This round returns from K mapping to recipe tuning, while still staying inside the same family and on a deployment-relevant point rather than retreating all the way to the K128 anchor."],"next_hypotheses":["If lower `AUXK_ALPHA` improves `K=96`, keep the same K fixed and continue recipe refinement there before revisiting other K values.","If lower `AUXK_ALPHA` does not help, treat the current `K=96/signum/LR=1.6e-3` recipe as close to saturated and move to another single recipe axis.","If reducing `AUXK_ALPHA` hurts stability or quality, the current auxiliary pressure is likely already appropriate for this near-anchor reduced-cost point."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
