research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0066.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 65 established `two_stage_residual` as the new mainline by materially beating the previous `gated` K128 control under the matched `signum`/`2.0e-3` recipe, so the highest-value next step is to convert that one-off probe into a clean mainline baseline before touching learning rate or optimizer. This round answers one question only: does the same `two_stage_residual` K128 EF12 `signum` `2.0e-3` recipe reproduce a similarly strong curve as a stable baseline worth tuning from, or was Round 65 an overoptimistic single run.","summary":"Run a clean baseline repeat for the new `two_stage_residual` mainline at `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3`, changing no recipe variable beyond promoting the family into baseline confirmation.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"confirm_baseline","family_name":"two_stage_residual","family_stage":"baseline","self_review":"This follows the mainline progression rule by staying within the same family and using the recommended next step of establishing a clean baseline before any LR or optimizer change. The round changes no substantive training variable, so the result will be easy to attribute and will tell us whether the promising staged-residual curve is robust enough to tune further.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"two_stage_residual"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 66 promotes `two_stage_residual` from matched probe winner to mainline candidate by running a clean baseline repeat before any recipe tuning.","Judge this round primarily by reproducibility of the training curve shape and final FVU relative to Round 65, not just by whether the endpoint is slightly above or below 0.1278.","If the baseline reproduces cleanly, the next mainline question should be a single learning-rate adjustment inside `two_stage_residual`; if it fails to reproduce, investigate stability before changing optimizer or K."],"next_hypotheses":["If the clean baseline reproduces the strong Round 65 curve, test one learning-rate adjustment within `two_stage_residual` next.","If the clean baseline is materially worse or less stable, rerun only if needed to separate variance from recipe instability before changing optimizer.","If the curve is strong early but plateaus oddly, use the next round for a single LR change rather than touching K or architecture."],"primary_variable":"baseline_confirmation"}
research/history_archive/10_20260321_011318/logs/agent_action_0003.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Return to the known-working TopK baseline at K=128 and slightly reduce learning rate to improve run stability after consecutive crashes without changing the architecture search surface.","summary":"Crash-recovery proxy run: use TopK at the K=128 anchor with a modest LR reduction to re-establish a stable quality baseline.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"stability","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline_comparison","self_review":"This does not advance architecture exploration, but crash recovery mode requires a conservative parameter-only step on the current best working setup. The main limitation is that it prioritizes stability over a large FVU jump this round.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"LR","value":"6e-4"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Entered crash recovery mode after consecutive gated-family crashes, so this round intentionally avoids code edits and new architecture exploration.","Using the TopK K=128 anchor with a small LR reduction is the safest way to refresh a trustworthy working quality baseline.","Do not treat this as a success unless it both runs cleanly and provides a usable FVU anchor for future comparisons."],"next_hypotheses":["If this TopK recovery run is stable, compare whether Adam further improves stability or FVU at the same K=128 anchor.","If stability is restored but FVU remains weak, resume architecture exploration from a different family rather than over-tuning TopK.","If this still crashes, investigate execution-layer/runtime causes before drawing conclusions about SAE quality."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0016.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 15 established `topk/signum/LR=1.6e-3/EF=12` at `K=64` as a valid new Pareto point, so the next most informative single-variable question is whether LUTurbo can push cost lower again without collapsing reconstruction. This round changes only `K`, moving from `64` to `32` while keeping the same family and recipe fixed, to measure the next step on the cost-quality frontier.","summary":"Continue the topk low-K tradeoff lane: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and reduce `K` from `64` to `32` to test whether a materially cheaper decomposition still yields an acceptable reconstruction curve.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the active topk family, changes exactly one primary variable, and follows directly from the new `K=64` keep result. The main risk is a sharp FVU jump at `K=32`, but mapping that boundary is now more valuable than more K128 recipe polishing because LUTurbo's objective is total online cost, not only anchor quality.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 15 added a credible `K=64` Pareto point on the accepted topk/signum/LR1.6e-3/EF12 backbone.","Round 16 continues the same low-K mapping by changing only `K` from 64 to 32.","Judge this run on frontier usefulness, not raw comparison to K128 alone: the key question is whether `K=32` remains deployably compatible with a tolerable quality drop for the lower online selection and summation cost."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=32` is still competitive enough, continue the same lane to `K=24` or `K=16` depending on curve shape and degradation size.","If `K=32` degrades sharply, `K=64` may be the practical low-K sweet spot for the current topk recipe.","If `K=32` is borderline but usable, compare it against `K=64` as a cost-quality tradeoff rather than against the K128 anchor alone."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0081.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`LR=1.6e-3` slightly regressed from the stable `2.0e-3` anchor, so the signum LR question is still unresolved on the upward side. A symmetric probe at `LR=2.4e-3` is the cleanest next move: it tests whether the stronger `lowrank_two_stage_residual` backbone still benefits from a slightly larger step size via faster early/mid descent without destabilizing late training.","summary":"Stay on the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` mainline and change only `LR` from `2.0e-3` to `2.4e-3`, keeping `ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_two_stage_residual`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and the baseline aux/runtime settings fixed. Judge the run by the full trajectory versus the `2.0e-3` and `1.6e-3` runs, especially whether the higher LR preserves stability while improving early/mid descent and final FVU; if it overshoots or degrades late, close the signum LR branch and keep `2.0e-3` as the operative mainline LR.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the required mainline sequence: same family, same K, same optimizer, EF explicitly fixed to 12, and only one primary variable changes. The risk is that `2.4e-3` may overshoot on a backbone that already looked well-tuned at `2.0e-3`, but that is exactly the remaining single-variable question before it is defensible to stop LR tuning and move to optimizer.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.4e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 81 completes the symmetric signum LR bracket for the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128/EF12 mainline by probing `LR=2.4e-3` after `1.6e-3` regressed slightly.","Interpretation should emphasize curve shape: if `2.4e-3` improves early speed but harms late stability or finish, keep `2.0e-3` as the mainline LR and open the optimizer branch next."],"next_hypotheses":["If `LR=2.4e-3` also regresses or destabilizes, lock `signum` + `LR=2.0e-3` as the mainline recipe and switch only `OPTIMIZER` next.","If `LR=2.4e-3` wins clearly, run exactly one clean confirmation on that higher-LR anchor before trying optimizer.","Do not touch loss, preprocess, or K until the signum LR verdict is closed for `lowrank_two_stage_residual` at K128."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0041.json:1:{"change_type":"edit_perf_code","command":"run","env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"group_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"expected_win":"explore_unknown","experiment_tier":"proxy","family_name":"group_topk","family_stage":"prototype","hypothesis":"The recent `first_step_timeout` crashes are not specific to `group_topk`: the gated AUXK=0 recovery run also advanced through the first few microbatches and then stalled at the first optimizer step. That points to a shared training-path bottleneck rather than an architecture verdict. Replacing CUDA's per-step fired-latent `cat`+advanced-index update with an incremental boolean fired mask in `sparsify/trainer.py` should remove that first-step spike and let the unresolved `group_topk` K=128 proxy run complete under the current strongest regime.","needs_sanity":true,"next_hypotheses":["If the patched `group_topk` run completes and is competitive with gated at K=128, keep the family alive and start stabilizing its grouped-selection design inside `sparsify/`.","If the run completes normally but `group_topk` is still clearly worse on FVU, retire hard grouped competition and move to a more expressive new family rather than more selector variants.","If `group_topk` still hits a first-step timeout after this shared trainer fix, stop spending rounds on it and treat the remaining issue as a deeper execution-path incompatibility."],"notes_to_memory":["Rounds 38 and 40 both progressed through several microbatches before timing out, so the failure signature is now shared across `group_topk` and gated rather than isolated to one family.","The stall aligns with the first optimizer step, which makes shared post-accumulation bookkeeping a stronger suspect than encoder forward quality.","This round patches `sparsify/trainer.py` so CUDA tracks fired latents with an incremental per-step boolean mask instead of building a large concatenated index tensor at step end, while preserving the deferred NPU path."],"primary_variable":"code_fix","self_review":"This is the narrowest defensible follow-up because the unresolved issue is now a shared runtime bottleneck, and another parameter-only probe would risk repeating the same crash without adding architectural evidence. The main risk is that the timeout may come from optimizer or logging overhead instead, but the logs make the fired-latent bookkeeping on the first optimizer step the best current target.","summary":"Patch the shared trainer dead-feature bookkeeping to reduce first-optimizer-step overhead on CUDA, then retry the blocked `group_topk` K=128 proxy comparison under the gated anchor settings.","touched_files":["sparsify/trainer.py"]}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0071.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 70 answered the first `two_stage_residual` LR probe negatively: lowering `LR` from `2.0e-3` to `1.6e-3` produced a uniformly worse curve, with weaker start, weaker mid-course descent, and a worse endpoint than the archived baseline. The next single mainline question, still within the prescribed LR-before-optimizer order, is whether a modest upward shift improves early and mid-course descent without destabilizing training: does raising `LR` to `2.4e-3` beat or at least match the archived `2.0e-3` `two_stage_residual` baseline on full-curve shape?","summary":"Stay on the `two_stage_residual` mainline and revert to the archived baseline recipe, changing only `LR` from `2.0e-3` to `2.4e-3` while keeping `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and the baseline aux/runtime settings fixed. Judge this run by the whole trajectory against the archived `2.0e-3` baseline, especially whether the higher step size improves descent without introducing instability or a worse finish.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"two_stage_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This remains on the active mainline family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, uses an allowed `K`, and changes exactly one primary variable: `lr`. It follows the required sequence because the clean baseline is already established and Round 70 showed that lower LR is not the right direction; the highest-value next question is the symmetric upward LR probe before opening the optimizer branch. The main risk is overshooting and adding instability, but that is precisely what this single-variable test is designed to resolve.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.4e-3"},{"key":"BATCH_SIZE","value":"1"},{"key":"GRAD_ACC_STEPS","value":"8"},{"key":"MICRO_ACC_STEPS","value":"1"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 70 established that `two_stage_residual` with `LR=1.6e-3` is uniformly worse than the archived `2.0e-3` baseline across start, mid, and end of the curve, so the lower-LR branch should not be favored.","Round 71 is the complementary within-family LR probe: test `LR=2.4e-3` against the archived `two_stage_residual` baseline at `K=128`, `EF=12`, and `signum`, and judge it by full-curve shape rather than endpoint alone."],"next_hypotheses":["If `LR=2.4e-3` improves endpoint or gives a clearly stronger overall curve than `2.0e-3`, archive it as the new `two_stage_residual` mainline recipe.","If `LR=2.4e-3` is noisier or clearly worse, keep `2.0e-3` as the settled signum LR and move to the optimizer question next.","If `LR=2.4e-3` is mixed, do at most one final LR-localization round before changing optimizer."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0250.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"On the directly compatible `topk` line, increasing `K` from 96 to 160 should produce a materially better `<0.5x` Pareto point, likely around the low-0.18 FVU range at about 0.41x total_cost, while avoiding the recent `factorized_topk` pattern of modest quality gains paired with worse throughput.","summary":"Use `topk` as the next low-cost mainline probe, anchored to r242 and changing only `K` to 160. Final reconstruction formula remains `x_hat = Σ_{i in TopK(x)} α_i(x) b_i`, where all `b_i` come from one static vector library, so this family is `直接兼容` with the LUTurbo/Lottable `查表 + 加权求和 + 选择性补偿` path. This is a strict single-variable step inside the target `<0.5x` region: estimated selection cost stays at the EF=1 topk baseline, deployment lookup rises with `K`, and combined cost should land near 0.41x, filling the gap between the existing 0.38x/0.1968 and 0.44x/0.1635 topk points. Recent `factorized_topk` rounds improved FVU only slightly while increasing runtime cost, so the cleaner frontier-building move is to continue the already monotone-improving topk K ladder.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is intentionally conservative: it does not open a new family, and it relies on the existing topk trend rather than a new mechanism. The tradeoff is that it will not teach much about new structure, but that is acceptable here because the current priority is to strengthen the `<0.5x` Pareto frontier with a deployable, directly compatible point and to avoid recipes that slow training without a commensurate FVU gain.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"K","value":"160"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Recent `factorized_topk` rounds remained far above the best low-cost topk points, and the wider scorer pass at r249 also reduced throughput to about 111k tok/s, so further factorized widening is currently a weak cost-quality bet.","The EF=1 `topk` K ladder has shown consistent FVU improvement from K=96 to K=128 to K=192 without any compatibility risk; an untested midpoint K=160 is the cleanest next `<0.5x` frontier probe."],"next_hypotheses":["If `topk` K=160 lands near the expected ~0.18 FVU at ~0.41x, test `K=176` next to refine the mid-right edge of the `<0.5x` frontier.","If `topk` K=160 underperforms the monotone trend, shift the next round to a different directly compatible low-cost selector family instead of continuing dense K sweeps.","If runtime regresses disproportionately at K=160, treat that as a system-side warning and prefer lower-cost frontier densification over larger-K topk pushes."],"reference_round":242}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0002.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The new JumpReLU family deserves its first proxy measurement at the K=128 quality anchor; learnable thresholds with smooth gating may suppress weak activations and beat plain TopK FVU before any cost-oriented moves.","summary":"Run the first proxy comparison for the `jumprelu` family at K=128 using the prototype already added under `sparsify/`. Keep the round focused on establishing whether this family can materially improve the anchor-quality regime before any smaller-K or throughput tradeoffs.","change_type":"parameter_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"jumprelu","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is the narrowest coherent follow-up because there is still no empirical signal for the new family. Risk remains runtime overhead from the dense encode path, but that should be interpreted as implementation cost unless quality is also clearly unpromising.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"jumprelu"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_INIT_THRESHOLD","value":"0.15"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_BANDWIDTH","value":"0.10"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 2 uses the existing JumpReLU prototype for its first proxy measurement at the K=128 quality anchor.","No additional code changes were needed; this round is intended to establish initial quality and runtime signal for the new family."],"next_hypotheses":["If JumpReLU beats the TopK K=128 anchor on proxy, tune threshold initialization and bandwidth as the family-specific stabilization pass.","If JumpReLU quality is competitive but runtime is poor, follow with a code-fix round to optimize the encode path rather than discarding the family.","If JumpReLU clearly misses the quality target, explore a different architecture family with stronger routing structure instead of continuing weak local tuning."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
