research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0164.json:1:{"change_type":"param_only","command":"run","env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"}],"expected_win":"explore_unknown","experiment_tier":"proxy","family_name":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"prototype","hypothesis":"Matched architecture probe on lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual with K=128, EF=2, OPTIMIZER=signum, LR=3.0e-3 unchanged. Final reconstruction remains x_hat = U(Vx) + Σ_m pi_m c_m + Σ_i alpha_i^(1) b_i + Σ_j alpha_j^(2) b_j, where U(Vx) is a static low-rank trunk library, {c_m} is a static codebook library, and {b_i} is a static residual dictionary; only the stage-1/stage-2 budget split changes to a front-loaded 75/25 allocation. This is 扩展兼容 and exports cleanly to LUTurbo as trunk lookup + codebook lookup + two residual sparse lookups. Because this variant reuses the parent encoder modules, its selection-cost profile should stay matched to the mainline EF=2 point instead of introducing extra router/bucket scorer cost; the probe asks whether front-loading support budget improves low-EF reconstruction enough to justify future tuning.","needs_sanity":false,"next_hypotheses":["If this probe is clearly worse in FVU or runtime, return directly to the mainline lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual recipe next round.","If it is competitive at similar runtime, the next single-variable follow-up is STAGE1_RATIO tuning within this asymmetric family rather than opening another new architecture family."],"notes_to_memory":["Compatibility: 扩展兼容. Export formula: x_hat = U(Vx) + Σ_m pi_m c_m + Σ_i alpha_i^(1) b_i + Σ_j alpha_j^(2) b_j.","Probe choice rationale: matched to the current mainline formula class and likely budget-safe at EF=2, unlike routed/bucketed matched probes which add extra selector layers and risk policy rejection on selection cost.","This round is intentionally only an architecture probe; K=128, EF=2, OPTIMIZER=signum, LR=3.0e-3 stay fixed."],"primary_variable":"architecture","self_review":"Upside is bounded because this family only changes a fixed stage split and was not strong historically at higher-EF regimes, so a null result is plausible. Still, it is the cleanest policy-safe matched probe that isolates architecture without confounding cost increases.","summary":"Run one matched architecture probe with ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual and keep the mainline recipe otherwise unchanged. It preserves LUTurbo-exportable static-library reconstruction and mainline-like selection cost, so the result will answer whether asymmetric budget allocation is worth any continued attention in the current low-EF regime.","touched_files":[]}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/logs/agent_action_0099.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 98 was the first signum LR probe on `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` to beat the archived `LR=2.0e-3` K128 baseline, so before opening the optimizer branch the next single question should be whether `LR=2.4e-3` is a reproducible new anchor rather than a one-off improvement. Re-running the exact same `2.4e-3` recipe is the cleanest way to judge whether the full curve remains stronger than the `2.0e-3` and `1.6e-3` runs, especially in early/mid descent and late stability, rather than trusting the endpoint alone.","summary":"Stay on the `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` mainline and run a clean confirmation of the promising higher-LR recipe with `ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.4e-3`, changing no other recipe variable.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"confirm_baseline","family_name":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays within the same family, keeps `K` and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and changes no new axis beyond confirming the only signum LR setting that has actually improved the endpoint so far. The tradeoff is spending one round on confirmation instead of opening the optimizer branch immediately, but that is justified because the mainline anchor should be localized on a reproducible LR before optimizer comparisons are made.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.4e-3"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 99 is a clean confirmation run for the first improved signum LR candidate on `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`: `LR=2.4e-3` at `K=128`, `EF=12`, and `OPTIMIZER=signum`.","Judge this round by curve-shape repeatability against the archived `LR=2.0e-3`, `LR=1.6e-3`, and Round 98 `LR=2.4e-3` runs, not by endpoint alone.","Only after confirming whether `LR=2.4e-3` is a stable anchor should the optimizer branch open on this family."],"next_hypotheses":["If `LR=2.4e-3` reproduces the stronger curve or endpoint, promote it to the operative signum mainline LR and test `OPTIMIZER=adam` next at that settled recipe.","If the `LR=2.4e-3` repeat falls back to a near-tie or worse than `LR=2.0e-3`, close the signum LR branch with `LR=2.0e-3` as the operative anchor and test `OPTIMIZER=adam` next there.","Do not change loss, preprocess, or `K` until the optimizer question has been isolated from the settled signum baseline."],"primary_variable":"baseline_confirmation"}
