research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0134.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Adam may be failing specifically in the brittle low-K bucketed regime rather than across the whole `bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` family. Testing the same EF=16 recipe at `K=64` isolates optimizer sensitivity on a stronger mid-K frontier point and could improve FVU without sacrificing a non-dominated tradeoff.","summary":"Run a parameter-only optimizer probe on `bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` at `K=64, EF=16`, switching from `signum` to `adam` while keeping the rest of the recipe fixed. This checks whether the recent Adam failure was K32-specific and gives a cleaner read on whether Adam is worth keeping alive on the current leading family.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This stays within the operator-requested runtime axes and avoids unsupported loss-function plumbing through the fixed launcher. It is not the highest-value smaller-K target, but after Adam and Hadamard both failed at K32, a K64 control is the cleanest way to determine whether Adam is broadly bad under EF=16 or only bad in the tightest bucketed regime.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"64"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 134 should use `bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` at `K=64` as the optimizer control after Adam failed badly at K32 under the same EF=16 family.","Keep the override set minimal and explicit so attribution stays on optimizer rather than architecture, EF, or aux drift.","If Adam is still poor at K64, treat `adam` as broadly unpromising for the current EF=16 bucketed backbone and stop spending rounds on it without a stronger reason."],"next_hypotheses":["If Adam improves the K64 bucketed point, propagate Adam to K96 or K128 to see whether the gain is a general mid/high-K effect before revisiting K32 with a retuned LR.","If Adam is neutral or worse at K64, deprioritize optimizer swaps on the bucketed family and return to supported preprocessing probes on a different existing backbone.","If Adam is close but noisy at K64, run one confirmatory repeat on the same target rather than branching to another architecture."],"primary_variable":"optimizer"}
