research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0131.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Now that bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual has replaced the old high-K anchor at EF=16, the highest-value next test is whether an optimizer change can further improve a smaller-K frontier point without changing architecture or capacity; specifically, Adam on the strong K=32 bucketed backbone may reduce FVU enough to tighten the low-cost Pareto region.","summary":"Run a parameter-only optimizer ablation on the current K=32 bucketed backbone: keep architecture, K, EF, and LR fixed, and swap `signum` for `adam` to test whether optimizer choice improves the low-K frontier under the new EF=16 regime.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline_optimizer_probe","self_review":"This follows the operator priority shift by probing optimizer rather than inventing a new architecture, and it keeps attribution clean by changing only the optimizer on an existing frontier model. Keeping LR fixed at 3.2e-3 makes the result easier to interpret, though it may understate Adam's ceiling if it needs a different tuned LR.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 131 should pivot from K-axis mapping to the operator-requested optimizer dimension now that bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual owns the EF=16 anchor and mid-K lane.","Probe optimizer on K=32 first because improving a smaller-K frontier point is more valuable than chasing an already-strong K=128 anchor, and K=32 is the cheapest currently exposed bucketed frontier slot."],"next_hypotheses":["If Adam improves K=32 materially, propagate the same optimizer test to K=64 on the bucketed family to see whether the gain generalizes across the mid-K frontier.","If Adam is neutral or worse at K=32 with fixed LR, keep signum as the bucketed default and pivot next to a preprocessing or loss-function ablation on the same K=32 backbone.","If Adam destabilizes training, avoid coupled LR retuning immediately and instead test a different optimizer that is more likely to behave well under the existing 3.2e-3 recipe."],"primary_variable":"optimizer"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0104.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After five non-improving rounds, minor recipe tweaks on the current routed and plain winners are no longer the highest-value move. A fundamentally different architecture is warranted, and the best next test is `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` at the smaller frontier-relevant `K=24` anchor: grouping may regularize support allocation in the mid-K regime without the instability that caused routed collapse at `K=32`, potentially creating a new non-dominated point below the current plain two-stage soft-codebook `K=24` frontier.","summary":"Run one architecture-comparison experiment at `K=24` with `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual`, keeping `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed. Success criterion: beat the current `K=24` frontier anchor FVU (`0.09216673672199249`) and determine whether grouped soft-codebook support is a better mid-K backbone than continued tuning of routed/plain two-stage variants.","change_type":"param_only","expected_win":"frontier_improve","family_name":"lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"incubating","self_review":"This follows the severe-stagnation policy by switching to a genuinely different built-in architecture instead of another scalar tweak. I chose `K=24` because smaller-K improvements are more valuable than chasing the already-strong high-K anchors, and this slot is still owned by the plain family with room for a different architecture to win. The main risk is that grouping helps only at low K and will not outperform the plain two-stage soft-codebook recipe in the mid-K band.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Severe stagnation policy triggered after five non-improving rounds, so round 104 should stop scalar exploitation and switch to a fundamentally different architecture.","Choose `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` as the next architecture because it already showed some promise at low K and offers a qualitatively different support-allocation mechanism without introducing new code.","Target `K=24` first because improving a smaller-K frontier slot is more valuable than additional high-K probing, and the routed family has already shown instability when pushed downward."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` wins at `K=24`, run the same fixed recipe at `K=32` to map whether grouping is broadly useful in the mid-K regime.","If it is close but slightly behind at `K=24`, consider one confirmatory run at `K=32` before discarding the grouped soft-codebook family.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, reject this grouped branch for mid-K and move the next severe-stagnation round to a different existing soft-codebook family such as `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual`."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
